        summary: "Sellers always think their property is worth more than it is. In affordable housing, the gap between what sellers ask and what deals can support is enormous — and if you don't understand how to value land correctly, you'll either overpay and blow your capital stack, or lose deals because you don't know how to justify your number.  Dr. Merritt's framework: in affordable housing, land is worth zero. Not metaphorically — structurally. If you're using tax credits and subsidy to finance the project, that's because the deal can't support traditional debt and equity at normal returns. Which means there's no room for expensive land. The amount of subsidy you need is in direct inverse proportion to what the land is worth.  For market-rate deals, she backs into land value from her pro forma: start with all hard and soft costs, project cash flows, figure out what return your investor requires, and then start adding land value until the return drops to just above your hurdle — say, 16.5% when the investor requires 16%. Whatever that number is, that's the most you can pay for the site. Not what the seller thinks it's worth. Not what the appraiser will say six months from now in due diligence. Your analysis, based on what you can build and what return you can deliver.  For affordable deals, she checks comps — what did the last person pay for something similar? — and estimates a reasonable per-unit land cost based on that. Then she runs her preliminary underwriting to confirm the numbers work. The appraisal comes later, in due diligence. At this stage, she's doing her own analysis to decide whether it's worth pursuing at all.",
