        id: 3,
        title: "Due Diligence: What You Need Before You're Locked In",
        summary: "Once you're under contract, the clock starts. You have a limited window to discover problems that would change your decision to buy — and the cost of finding them now is nothing compared to the cost of finding them after closing. Dr. Merritt has a clear checklist of non-negotiables, developed over 28 years of deals and a few hard lessons.  Title comes first, always. Pull it early and look carefully. You will find things: unpaid water bills, old liens, easements, strange ownership histories. One deal had an owner who owed $250,000 in water bills. That has to be addressed in the contract — either the seller pays at closing, or it becomes your problem. You need to know before you commit.  Phase 1 environmental is required by any lender anyway — do it during due diligence, not after. Soils testing is undervalued: Dr. Merritt has seen people tie up properties only to discover the ground is full of clay and can't support the structure they planned. You can't build on clay. That's a deal-killer you want to find in diligence, not at groundbreaking.  Preliminary market analysis — not a full study, but enough to confirm that the key factors align with the QAP if you're doing a tax credit deal. Don't spend $15,000 on a full market study before you're sure the deal pencils. But do get enough analysis to know whether the threshold conditions are met.  Test fit: if you have an architect you've worked with, you can often get a test fit for free. This tells you whether you can actually build the program you're planning on this site. Zoning analysis is part of this — confirm that what you want to build is what the zoning allows, or that you understand exactly what it would take to change it.",
