        summary: "Finding a site and underwriting it is the straightforward part. Getting a seller to hold while you spend 18–24 months assembling financing — tax credit allocations, subsidy rounds, HUD commitments, construction lending — is where deals fall apart. Dr. Merritt has navigated this more times than she can count, and she's developed a clear-eyed view of how to manage it.  The environment has changed fundamentally. Before 2008, sellers would put properties under contract for a year or two while you figured out your financing. Those days are gone. Sellers today want to close now. Which means you're trying to hold a seller through a process that, by design, takes much longer than they want to wait.  Her tools: refundable and non-refundable deposits to buy contract extensions; seller notes and second trusts to get sellers liquid while giving yourself more time; relationships with lenders — especially CDFIs — who understand the affordable housing timeline and will work with you through delays in ways that traditional banks won't.  A real example: she had a site where she knew the seller was aging and needed liquidity now. She found a CDFI lender willing to do community development financing. Used a first trust loan to pay the seller seven figures upfront, and took a second trust from the seller on the property. Bought herself time to pursue the tax credit allocation. Three years later, she still hasn't gotten the allocation, has carried the site through multiple extension negotiations, and is working through how to keep the seller patient through one more round.  The lesson: always know your limits. What is the maximum you're willing to spend holding a site? At what point do you walk away? And always have a plan B before you need it.",
