        title: "Ownership Interest vs. Economic Interest — Know the Difference",
        summary: "One of the most commonly misunderstood aspects of JV structuring — and one of the most important to get right — is the difference between what you own and what you earn. They don't have to be the same number, and in many of Dr. Merritt's deals, they're not.  Ownership interest is about control, market positioning, and qualifying for programs. Being the majority owner means you can go to market as the lead developer, qualify for MWBE certifications, and represent the project as yours. It also affects how lenders and investors perceive who's running the deal.  Economic interest is about how the developer fee and cash flows are split. This is what you actually get paid.  Dr. Merritt has a deal in Cleveland where she is the majority owner. Her economic interest is lower than her ownership stake — because her partners are providing all the capital and all the guarantees. She runs everything. They write the checks. They don't interfere. It's her best JV right now. The separation of ownership and economics makes that possible.  The reverse also happens: she has deals where a nonprofit is the 51% owner (for community credibility, for grant eligibility, for political reasons), but Dr. Merritt holds a higher economic interest — 75% of the developer fee — because she's providing the financial guarantees and doing all the development work.  You can also split economic interest differently across deal phases. If you're doing all the development work, you might negotiate a higher share of the developer fee but a lower share of the refinance proceeds in 10 or 15 years, when you're no longer the one managing the asset. Tie your economics to your actual labor.",
