        summary: "Dr. Merritt is candid about her worst JV experiences, and they cluster around three problems: partners who don't perform their roles, partners who control the money and make bad decisions because of it, and deal structures — usually proposed by national developers — designed to extract maximum value from smaller partners.  The non-performing partner: she has a deal right now where her team is doing significantly more work than they were initially asked to, while the other party does less. The result: her overhead is being consumed covering work she shouldn't be doing, without commensurate compensation. Her lesson for future deals: build dilution rights into the structure from day one. If a partner doesn't perform their defined role, their interest is reduced. She doesn't have that in her current structure, and it's costing her.  The money-controls-everything problem: in half her deals, her partners are less experienced than she is but hold the financial leverage. They can make bad decisions about lenders, contractors, and timelines — decisions that affect her outcomes — because they're the ones providing the guarantees. She had a partner choose a lender she knew had nearly put her out of business, and she had no recourse because it wasn't her call. Her rule going forward: she won't do deals with someone who doesn't understand enough about real estate development to make sound decisions.  The national developer overhead trap: a national developer wanted her to bring deals to their partnership. The term sheet included a clause where their overhead — starting at seven figures — would be deducted before the developer fee split. Meaning she'd receive her percentage of whatever was left after they'd already paid themselves. She walked. She later saw the same clause in a deal another developer brought to her attention. It's a pattern. Recognize it.",
