        id: 3,
        title: "Community Engagement Is Development Work — Not a Checkbox",
        summary: "Dr. Merritt held community meetings every single month for ten months on the 9410 Hough project before closing. She ran printed surveys on facade colors. She partnered with Famicos, a local community organization, to distribute those surveys and build neighborhood relationships. She held the project's community meetings in accessible locations where residents could actually show up.  This wasn't charity. It was development practice.  9410 required a zoning change. Zoning changes require council approval. Council members respond to their constituents. If a single organized group had complained to the council member about the project, it could have stopped the closing — regardless of the merits of the deal. The community engagement process neutralized that risk. Dr. Merritt went through a ten-month process of being known in that neighborhood, answering questions, incorporating feedback, and building relationships — so that when the zoning change came up, there was no organized opposition.  She's also seen community engagement done badly — or not at all — and watched deals die because of it. Developers who show up for the first time at a public hearing, having never spoken to the neighborhood, face communities that are understandably hostile. That hostility can kill approvals, generate political opposition, and create legal challenges that delay projects by years.  There are always a few people in every community who will oppose development regardless of its merits. Dr. Merritt's advice: 'Know your homework, know the details, understand the community, so you can clap back. Don't let those people scare you.' Have the data. Know the history. Be prepared to respond to misinformation directly and credibly. Then let the majority of residents who support your project be heard.",
